  PlotRange->{{0, 953.}, {0, 388.5}}]], "Output",
 CellMargins->{{Automatic, Automatic}, {10, 6}},
 ShowCellLabel->False,
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"17e1ecfe-28e1-4c51-8a7a-d277e56dd004"],

Cell["\<\
The headline result. As execution noise \[Epsilon] rises (left to right), the \
evolutionarily stable composition of strategies shifts \[Dash] from a \
coexistence of generous reciprocators to a collapse into unconditional \
defection.\
\>", "Text",
 CellMargins->{{70, 70}, {2, 14}},
 FontSize->11,
 FontSlant->Italic,
 FontColor->GrayLevel[
  0.35],ExpressionUUID->"d4a70152-946c-4a01-9881-3566973b03c0"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Abstract", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"8eb9a755-c871-43aa-a3df-6620156dc391"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In 1980 Robert Axelrod ran a now-famous computer tournament for the ",
 StyleBox["iterated Prisoner's Dilemma",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ". The winner was the simplest entrant of all \[Dash] ",
 StyleBox["Tit-for-Tat",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ": cooperate first, then copy your opponent. This notebook reproduces that \
tournament in the Wolfram Language, with the classic strategies plus modern \
entrants (Generous Tit-for-Tat, Pavlov, Gradual, and Press \[Dash] Dyson \
zero-determinant strategies)."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{60, 60}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->14,
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.98, 0.96, 0.9],ExpressionUUID->"edfd2524-de46-4860-b56b-6325a1ba115a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It then does two things Axelrod's setup hints at but does not show. ",
 StyleBox["First",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ", an ",
 StyleBox["evolutionary",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " tournament: we let populations of strategies reproduce in proportion to \
their success and ask which mixture is stable. ",
 StyleBox["Second",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ", we add ",
 StyleBox["noise",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " \[Dash] a small probability that an intended move is mis-executed \[Dash] \
and show that the evolutionarily stable mixture ",
 StyleBox["depends on the noise level",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ". Finally, in the spirit of an automated-research loop, we let a search \
algorithm ",
 StyleBox["discover",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " memory-one strategies that beat Tit-for-Tat under noise."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{60, 60}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->14,
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.98, 0.96, 0.9],ExpressionUUID->"32298860-a697-4d2e-a60f-eb66df5be4e0"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
1. The Prisoner's Dilemma, and why iteration changes everything\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c380b95d-3e34-426b-84b8-6ddce3eea5e5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Two players each choose, simultaneously, to ",
 StyleBox["cooperate",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " (C) or ",
 StyleBox["defect",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " (D). The payoffs satisfy ",
 StyleBox["T > R > P > S",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["2R > T + S",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 ". With the classic Axelrod values ",
 StyleBox["T=5, R=3, P=1, S=0",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 ":"
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"f0eb2eb7-3a96-4ddc-86db-210e7ccffde3"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {"", 
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{"opp", " ", "C"}],
      FontSlant->Italic], 
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{"opp", " ", "D"}],
      FontSlant->Italic]},
    {
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{"I", " ", "C"}],
      FontSlant->Italic], 
     RowBox[{"R", "=", "3"}], 
     RowBox[{"S", "=", "0"}]},
    {
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{"I", " ", "D"}],
      FontSlant->Italic], 
     RowBox[{"T", "=", "5"}], 
     RowBox[{"P", "=", "1"}]}
   },
   GridBoxDividers->{
    "Columns" -> {False, {True}, False}, "Rows" -> {False, {True}, False}}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",
 CellMargins->{{80, 50}, {8, 
  8}},ExpressionUUID->"f6ee4d57-377a-4003-9d9e-a00be6ef8623"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In a ",
 StyleBox["single",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " game, defection strictly dominates: whatever the opponent does, you score \
more by defecting. Yet mutual cooperation (R=3 each) beats mutual defection \
(P=1 each). That is the dilemma. Axelrod's insight was that when the game is ",
 StyleBox["repeated",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ", the shadow of the future can sustain cooperation \[Dash] a strategy can \
reward cooperation and punish defection in later rounds."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"f8e6b7c5-e671-4a4a-a350-84166c3a102a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Encoding strategies in the Wolfram Language", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"7fa1d72d-2643-47b2-8acf-8fdc2d390a3c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We encode ",
 StyleBox["C = 1",
  FontFamily->"Courier"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["D = 0",
  FontFamily->"Courier"],
 ". A strategy is a pure function of the two histories of actual moves; the \
smallest interesting family is the ",
 StyleBox["memory-one",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " strategies, parameterised by the probability of cooperating after each of \
the four possible previous outcomes:"
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"dc270f27-1bfb-41ab-99b5-693ef3bc721b"],

Cell["\<\
memOne[open_, {pCC_, pCD_, pDC_, pDD_}] := Function[{me, opp},
  If[me === {},
    If[RandomReal[] < open, 1, 0],
    If[RandomReal[] < {pCC, pCD, pDC, pDD}[[ stateIndex[Last[me], Last[opp]] \
]], 1, 0]]];

(* Tit-for-Tat: cooperate first, then copy the opponent's last move *)
TitForTat = memOne[1, {1, 0, 1, 0}];
Pavlov    = memOne[1, {1, 0, 0, 1}];   (* win-stay, lose-shift *)
GenerousTFT = memOne[1, {1, 1/3, 1, 1/3}];\
\>", "Input",
 CellMargins->{{60, 30}, {6, 6}},
 FontSize->11,ExpressionUUID->"0dfecf18-9d94-4e1e-b19e-92099da2bae2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The full library (in ",
 StyleBox["wolfram/axelrod.wl",
  FontFamily->"Courier"],
 ") has 13 strategies: AllC, AllD, Random, Tit-for-Tat, Suspicious TFT, \
Generous TFT, Tit-for-2-Tats, 2-Tits-for-Tat, Grim, Pavlov, Gradual, and two \
zero-determinant strategies (an extortioner and a generous one)."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"77631e10-f46d-4e47-8d38-ae90c4d8e255"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Noise: the trembling hand", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"11cc97cc-6b03-46f1-a53c-be23268e4019"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Real interactions are imperfect. We model ",
 StyleBox["execution noise",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ": each intended move is flipped with probability ",
 StyleBox["\[Epsilon]",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 ", and the opponent sees the ",
 StyleBox["actual",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " (post-noise) move. This single knob turns out to control everything that \
follows."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"c213b6b5-fbb6-4e39-8556-f6c667ac8341"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2. The classic round-robin (reproducing Axelrod 1980)", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"592b88de-2bae-496d-9039-b60967a0fb3b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Every strategy plays every strategy (including itself) for 200 rounds, \
repeated 100 times to average out randomness. Each strategy's score is its \
mean per-round payoff against the whole field. At ",
 StyleBox["\[Epsilon] = 0",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " (no noise) the ranking is:"
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{50, 50}, {6, 
  6}},ExpressionUUID->"9937af0d-dc50-481a-a744-12986a55e129"],

